Comment: A couple of games back, I played a Modern Benoni (beginning 2...c5) and won.  Time for something different: a King's Indian Defence.

Unusual move order, but nothing out of the ordinary.  Was White trying to invite a Benoni?
Certainly 3...c5 was playable, but I had already determined what opening I was going to play.
Also playable were ...c6 or ...c5 here.  But I prefer the main lines anyway, which look to action on the K-side.

So far, a main line King's Indian.  But now White diverges...

I have to admit, I don't much like the sort of game that emerges from this kind of exchange, though my record on the Black side hasn't been too bad.  It proves very difficult for both sides to establish any kind of edge.  Against the more usual 7.0-0 I would probably have played 7...Nc6.
Yep: there go the Queens.  White could have tried the quite playable 8.Qc2, but then one would be inclined to wonder why the exchange on e5.

Better than 9.Nxe5 Nxe4!
Better than 9.Nxe5 Nxe4!
To protect the e-pawn.  Black has little to fear from 10.Nd5 (...c6!).
An interesting alternative was 10.0-0-0.
Unpinning the d7-knight.  Black dared not place the rook on e8 owing to 10...Re8? 11.Nb5! Rb8 12.Nxc7 Rf8 13.Nd5, with advantage.
(!?) Castling instead seems good here.  Is the knight headed for b3?
To prevent a knight's getting in to b5 or d5.
Aiming to relocate to or protect c5?  At any rate, there's not much doing on the K-side, so White redeploys.
The pin released, Black rook returns to d8.  But 12...b6 at once might have been preferable. This rook, however, move is by way of preparing for the bishop to depart from the c8-square.
Very mysterious and surprising.  I thought the knight would appear at b3 at some time... Here, the threat 15.Nxe5 is easily met.

This must have been White's main idea: to double rooks on the d-file.  As the pin at d7 would have been very uncomfortable, Black reacts at once...
This must have been White's main idea: to double rooks on the d-file.  As the pin at d7 would have been very uncomfortable, Black reacts at once...
(!) Preparing to challenge the double rooks in the d-file...

Now there is no pin.  All the same, Black is in no hurry to liquidate the rooks.  Note that both sides have played very cautiously, neither giving much away, neither over-committing to any positive action.  White has a very centralised position, which answers for the hole at d4.  Black is less compact, but has no real weaknesses to speak of.  This is a tough fight for both sides...
